{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti 2.87** states that a Brahmana can attain perfection (*siddhi*) solely through recitation (*japa*, or mantra-recitation), irrespective of performing other rites, and emphasizes that a true Brahmana is one who is friendly to all beings.[^1]\n\nThis verse concludes a passage extolling the superiority of *japa-yajña* (the sacrifice of recitation) over ritual sacrifices: \"The four domestic sacrifices, together with the prescribed ritual sacrifices, are not worth a sixteenth part of the *japa-yajña*.\"[^2]\n\n[^1]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-fc9632).\n[^2]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-2599c3).",
